es the complex set of relations that define citizens as opposed to noncitizens, free men versus slaves, men versus women, and Greeks versus barbarians. Whose Antigone? moves beyond the narrow confines critics have inherited from German idealism to reinvigorate debates over the meaning and significance of Antigone, situating it within a wider argument that establishes the salience of slavery as a structuring theme.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAntigone (Greek mythology) in literature. 0aFeminism in literature. 0aSlavery in literature. 4aLiterature : Drama. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Feminist Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438437569423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438437569/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles